Title: Warning. Smell before giving to your dog.

I contacted customer service and they said that due to the nature of the issue they would refund the amount paid. Thank goodness I noticed the smell before giving it to my dog!!  I’m gun-shy now so I went to get one at my local Pet Smart (absolutely no scent and same price) They told me that they would refund if there were any issues with it.  I think I am going to stick with buying these at Per Smart from now on because I won’t have a day or two delay if there is an issue.  My dog loves these by the way. Author: Customer Review
Title: My Choco Lab Found Nirvana (Thanks to a Cheesy Brick from the Himalayas?) ️
Body: Forget your downward dog yoga poses, folks. My chocolate lab, Saint, achieved true canine enlightenment thanks to this little brick of cheesy goodness from the Himalayas (seriously, it looks like something Indiana Jones would find in a temple).Saint's a notorious chewer. Tennis balls? Gone in 60 seconds. Squeaky toys? Last about as long as a politician's campaign promise. But this yak cheese chew? Oh, honey, this is a whole different ball game.Here's why it's 5 stars (and Luna's official "paw" of approval):Durability that puts diamonds to shame. Saint gnawed, chomped, and even tried to bury this thing (because apparently, cheese treasure needs hiding?). Three days later, she's still at it, and the chew barely looks like it's been touched.Calming effect worthy of a Dalai Lama. No more bouncing off the walls like a furry pinball. This yak chew has Saint in a state of zen focus, meticulously chipping away at her cheesy Everest. I swear, I can hear tiny "om" chants coming from her.All-natural goodness that even picky pups approve. No weird chemicals or mystery ingredients – just yak milk goodness. Luna's sensitive tummy is doing a happy dance, and her breath actually smells like...cheese? Weird, but somehow endearing.The bottom line: This Himalayan yak chew is like a chewable meditation retreat for your dog. It's quiet, it's long-lasting, and it turns your furry hurricane into a contented cheese sculptor. If you're tired of the constant toy carnage, give this a try. Just be prepared for some serious cheese-induced zen vibes around the house.Namaste, fellow dog owners. ‍♀️Bonus tip: If you're feeling adventurous, try microwaving the leftover bits for a few seconds. Saint goes absolutely nuts for the crunchy, puffed-up cheese nuggets. Just don't blame me if your dog starts demanding yak cheese souffle for every meal.
Style: Flavor Name: Cheese | Size: 3.3 Ounce (Pack of 1)

I've had a lot of dogs in my life and I really wish this product has been around for all of them.Literally just now as I'm writing this review my 4-year-old said "Mom, Mako is biting me and I'm watching my show!!" and since I know that means he's just teething and wants somebody to play with, I just gave him the bone and now he's laying on the couch next to him, chewing something other than my children and will be completely content for at least 20 minutes.These last like 2 weeks in our experience, you can see in the picture I took the last two bones that were chewed down to the last little nub and he still likes to chew on them every once in awhile but was super excited when I got a new one.My pup prefers the peanut butter or bacon flavor and again make sure it says hard on the front of the package before you buy because not all of the available flavors are the same hardness level. We are on number five now for our 16 week pup, all ordered from Amazon and I have yet to have any of them chip or seen any Pieces come off that could be dangerous to my puppy. It isn't smelly AT ALL and it doesn't stain furniture or have any greasy residue. Usually I just see what looks like little white pencil shavings left behind which I just vacuum up. These will be my go-to from now on and I recommend them to everybody now.

Author: Kenzie
Title: Hard but brittle
Body: My dog Eugene chews like it's his full-time job, so we're constantly experimenting with products that will last more than an hour for him. This product was recommended by word-of-mouth to me which is always a good sign, and I think after he devoured it in less than an hour I have some insights. This chew is very hard, it would be great for medium-strength chewers. However it's also brittle, so Eugene was basically breaking chips off of it and eating it like a candy bar. Additionally, the price point is a little steep for us given how long it lasted. Eugene is also not food-motivated at all, which makes him the ultimate connoisseur, and this was to him pretty tasty but nothing to write home about. Collectively it took him not very long to get through it but he wasn't so enthusiastic that it was all in one sitting. At one point he opted to go chew a stick in the grass instead. So, take what you will of that, my dog is an anomaly in a lot of ways but for us we will keep looking for his ideal chew. If my situation sounds familiar to you, I can say we've had some luck with antlers and buffalo cheek rolls.
Style: Flavor Name: Peanut Butter | Size: 3.3 Ounce (Pack of 1)

Author: Rachel
Title: Our dog loves these
Body: Himalayan chews are one of our dog's favorite things to chew on during the day, when we telework. It keeps her occupied for maybe an hour or so (she's a light chewer, so if your dog is a heavy chewer, this likely won't last more than 10 minutes). When the chew gets to be small (potential choking hazard), you can soak it in a glass of water overnight, and then pop the chew into the microwave the following morning for apx 30 seconds to 1 minute (wait for the chew to "pop") and then when it cools down, you can give it to your dog as another little treat. I'd recommend giving this chew to them outside, since the smell of it (post-microwave) is not pleasant. Take note - when you place the chew in the microwave, it should become much larger than what you put into the microwave. If it's not, then it's still a choking hazard for your pup.Long story short, these chews are great, our (samoyed) dog loves them, and there are options for still using these, even after your dog has chewed them all the way down to a small nub.

Author: Gnatty77Gnatty77
Title: READ THIS BEFORE BUYING!!
Body: I’d read about these yak chews and thought I’d give them a try as a last resort of sorts since my 10 month Basset hound goes through bones like crazy. She loves to chew but nothing lasts. She either eats the bone within minutes or tries to eat the ones that aren’t edible (nylabone type) and I have to take them away and throw them out which is a waste of $. I wanted something that would last a few days but also not splinter or cause indigestion or dental issues. And preferably, little mess. I purchased this pack of 2 Himalayan Happy Teeth yak chews (pb flavor) to try. First, let me say that she loves them. No problems w the flavor. But she ate it within 15 minutes, at most. These aren’t cheap and I’d hoped to get more for my $. At least a day! I was disappointed but upon further inspection of the back of the package and comparing it to the other large, single pack (original; 4 oz) & small 4-pack of chews I bought (churro flavor w chicken; 4 oz), I noticed a scale on the back of all of them. I saw that this pack was rated on the lower end (2). The other bag (same company) was rated an 8. Had I seen this before I made my purchase, I’d have ensured to get a harder density bone. The size DOES NOT have anything to do w how dense the bone is so don’t assume larger is harder. The scale will help you decide what’s best. It is extremely helpful in allowing owners the opportunity to pick the right yak chew just for your pet. If you’ve a large, senior dog w dental issues or weak teeth, pick a large, softer chew. If you’ve a small dog or a puppy who’s teething, pick a smaller, softer chew. Or anything in between! Since my medium sized dogs teeth are large, I’d prefer a large, harder chew (I’m sticking w the 8) until she’s an adult. I’m wondering how many people who said the bone didn’t last purchased them w out referring to the scale? So please read the entire back of the package to get a better idea of what will suit your dog. Let’s keep in mind that it’s almost impossible to find an edible YET SAFE bone that will last very long. That’s just how it goes w animals w big, sharp teeth that chew everything so I use common sense when comparing and rating. I don’t expect to get what I didn’t pay for but I do expect to get my moneys worth. Here’s what I learned. This feedback was based on a medium sized, 10 month old dog w no dental issues. The small chews that were rated 2 were gone in a few minutes while the large chew rated 2 lasted 15 minutes. The large chew rated 8 on the scale lasted 2-3 days. She chewed it for 8 hours straight, stopping only to sleep, when she first got it around 3pm and on/off throughout the next day and finally finished it by early evening on the 3rd. All that was left was a little 1.5 inch nub. After researching, I learnt that the nub can be soaked in water for 5 minutes then microwaved for a minute or so until it puffs out. (Watch it as it heats and take it out when you think it’s about to pop.) It’ll feel light w the texture akin to a pork rind. Once it cools, (it WILL be hot), you can let your dog eat it. It’ll be very crunchy and they Will absolutely love it!! After microwaving the nub of the yak chew (8), the result was similar to the non microwaved yak chew (2). I think that’s how they soften them so that they can be rated lower. Be warned, any chew that’s 8 or above will be very hard and dense. Impaction/breaking a tooth/choking would be my only concern w these chews but that goes for just about everything a dog chews. Owners should always maintain a watch over their dog while they chew on bones. I’d suggest a large chew for larger dogs because they won’t be able to get it totally inside their mouths and that’ll slow them down. Even if it’s an 8 on the scale but smaller, it’ll still fit in their mouth where all their teeth can work it into nothing in no time. I haven’t seen any issues w diarrhea or digestion since my dog has been eating them, but I’d check w your vet about how many is the right amount per week. As for mess, the softer the chew, the messier it seems though the churro flavor wasn’t too bad. This particular yak chew, Happy Teeth (2), stuck on my carpet but was easy to pick off w my fingers though the vacuum did no good especially once the crumbs dried. The (8) made hardly any mess at all but for the random crumb here or there. Best for the softer ones to be eaten outside or on a surface where the crumbs can be easily cleaned. I highly recommend this brand of Himalayan dog chew. Just don’t forget to check the scale before making your purchase. FYI: There are yak chew/bone holders available that aid your dog in keeping it in a position that’s easier for them to chew using a screw and prevents them from choking on the small piece. (The entire thing is very hard plastic.) Once the chew is a nub, you can remove it and microwave. They’re kind of expensive ($18-30) but I found one, Bonehead, for $5 w the available coupon. It only works w the larger bones-you might check for other holders for smaller bones-but did an excellent job of allowing my dog to grasp and gnaw on her yak chew. It also gave me peace of mind that she wouldn’t swallow or choke on the nub.If this was helpful, can you please hit the thumbs up button on the bottom! Thanks.
Style: Flavor Name: Cheese | Size: 3.3 Ounce (Pack of 1)

Title: Never again

Had to make her go the next 24 hours with no food at all to calm down her intestines, then fed her boiled chicken and rice. Seemed fine the next day, so I let her have the chew again since I couldn't imagine it was the problem because she was getting so little of it chewed off. BUT, that night she had diarrhea again, and again during the night. Back to chicken and rice and NO CHEW for the last 24 hours, and so far no problem today. Just wish I hadn't ordered another before realizing this.

Author: Heather B.
Title: Top-notch dog chew!
Body: I think I've found the perfect dog chew! Our dog loves cheese, so I figured she'd love this chew. I just didn't realize that we would love it so much, too! It's not smelly (thank goodness... I still have nightmarish flashbacks to the time I gave one of our dogs a cow hoof... ick!!!), it keeps her occupied, and I don't have to worry about her breaking or fracturing a tooth. We give our dog this chew sometimes in the evenings as a treat, and she chews on it for a few hours. It has lasted for well over a week, and she gradually whittles it down bit by bit (it starts looking a bit like a crinkle cut fry, LOL). And then, when it gets small enough that it might cause concern, we tried the trick of soaking it in warm water for five minutes, then microwaving it for around 45 seconds... What a miracle! It puffed right up! After letting it cool off (5 minutes to play it safe), it was the perfect final treat for our dog! Two thumbs up!
Style: Flavor Name: Cheese | Size: 3.3 Ounce (Pack of 1)

Author: Amazon Customer
Title: Longlasting and my dog LOVES it
Body: Be careful when it gets small, i recommend breaking up the cheese bits really small (i used my husbands axe), i soaked in water, heated in microwave. Then soaked again for hours into bits no bigger than kibble- he LOVES THEM, and i dont have to worry about him choking, or eating a puff too big and it causing blockage. For the bigger puffs i gave him (before soaking them as much as i did, and breaking apart as much as i do now) i found a chunk in his poop. Thats when i decided to do all the extra breaking apart and soaking. Its his favorite treat, not to mention longlasting. It lasted my teething 4 month old cattle dog a week. (Intermittent chewing each day). He started going through half a 12" standard bully stick in 2 hours- this captures his attention just as much, but lasts so much longer. Currently trying another brand- but this brand lasts MUCH longer, i recommend this one over the other. And the smell? Barely any when im up in his face. This brand is less smelly than the other im trying, which i need to be at least a foot away before smelling anything, and i DONT want to smell it.I recommend this brand; spend the extra few dollars, its worth it.

Author: AnetoAneto
Title: Definitely higher density.
Body: I was hesitant to purchase these cheese chews from a different brand because the other cheese bones were starting to become too brittle. Our pup devoured the last bone in a day. Even though the labeling is for a 55lbs & under. This cheese bone has lasted longer than the other brand. My pup is 88lbs and it has been a struggle to find appropriate chew toys. This bone must have a higher density of the ingredients or the processing is better. There has not been any shards, and this is day day 3.UPDATE:  I guess it was the luck of the drawThe left one is the one was delivered on February 7th. This was one lasted 1 afternoon/evening.  The one on the left is the 1st cheese bone that I bought on February 5th. Lasted until Febuary 12th.even though there is some left, we aren't going to give it back incase he breaks it into pieces.Today I recieved the Himalayan  Dog chew for dogs 55lbs and over. I don't even have open the package to see that this one isn't going to make it through 1 day. It has pale yellow side (soft Cheese) and has a sharp corners (the first place to start chewing and subsequent  breaking), and this one has an actual crack down the middle.  Not acceptable for me.

Author: Brianna
Title: These bones almost killed my dog!
Body: So, we’ve been buying these for our English bulldog for about a year now. Initially, we loved them (she realllly loved them!). We were always a little concerned about the potential of a choking hazard (pieces being bit off, as our dog frequently did). Yesterday, our dog started vomiting - and a lot! It lasted through the day. This morning, she was much worse. Not eating and not even drinking water. She became weak and couldn’t even walk. When we took her to the vet, they did x-rays and saw that she had an obstruction. We ended up having to do surgery because of how bad it was. My dog is literally in surgery right now. The doctor just called us and told us she had a piece of this bone stuck in her stomach!! We’re out $1700 because of this bone. I’m so mad right now. Had we not taken the proper steps, the doc said she wouldn’t have made it. I will not ever purchase one of these bones again. I saw so many reviews saying similar things and I’m kicking myself for not listening. Do not buy these bones!!!! No matter how talented or aggressive of a chewer you have (because that’s what we thought) do not give these to your furbaby. Still can’t believe that this happened!
Style: Flavor Name: Cheese | Size: 3.3 Ounce (Pack of 1)

Body: It seems with these there's generally a much harder variety and a much softer variety. I have tried many chews from this brand in many different packagings, but I never know which one I'm going to get until I can look at the actual chew.I bought three of these hoping to get the very hard ones that my pup chews on for a month, until finally it's old enough it's not so interesting anymore and I can make the end nub into a puff to treat her. Instead, I got three of the very soft ones. I gave her the first one this morning and she ate half in one sitting and only stopped because I took it away (worried eating the whole thing in one go would upset her stomach). Obviously they taste fantastic, and it kept her occupied for most of two hours. These do have a smell, but I find it to be a pleasant one (much better than the stinky chunks of dead animal you get in real bones). I just wish I'd been able to get the harder kind that last longer. Body: Something seriously changed on this product. I have been feeding to my dog for 4 years since he was a puppy. It would take him about a month to eat a large size chew. For about 4 months now every time I give him one he literally eats them in an hour. Before he would almost had to grind it with his teeth. Now he is able to break it into smaller chunks and gulp it all up in two hours or less. Not only that, the last one that I gave him 3 weeks ago. He is still pooping chunks and today he threw up maybe the equivalent of half a chew. Never again. Definitely not healthy for him to have it in his stomach this long and luckily he didn’t get a blockage as he has been eating okay.

Author: Jessica
Title: NOT OKAY  **updated**  probably okay?
Body: Read below for my original review.  I just learned that a dog that goes to doggie daycare, that we had been in contact with a few days prior to the episode had the exact same symptoms without any yak treats to blame. I'm now under the impression that my dog had caught a virus that was just coincidence with a new food type introduced at the same time. Poor pup. I'm still nervous about trying another one though.  Changed my review to three stars because my dog did enjoy it quite a bit.I was really excited for this as a replacement for the nasty smelling bully sticks that my dog loves but also burns through. When I got it out of the package it smelled nice and felt really firm and I had high hopes. My dog loved it! She chewed on it off and on for about two hours throughout the evening. Only made it through about 10% of the chew, so she hadn't digested that much of it.  At 2:45 in the morning my dog is crying loudly and barking in her crate, which she has never done before. I took her outside to potty and she had really bad diarrhea. I told her good girl for making it outside, offered her a drink of water and put her back to bed. I woke up at 5:30 to get ready for my day and i heard her very quietly whimpering. She had puked in her crate at some point also, and then had more diarrhea outside. Clearly, the one i got either was contaminated or something. It was very disappointing to have to throw it away for making my dog so sick. :(  I will never buy this type of chew again.
Style: Flavor Name: Cheese | Size: 3.3 Ounce (Pack of 1)

Author: Emma J. GibbonEmma J. Gibbon
Title: Potentially Dangerous - Avoid
Body: These were our go-to for a little while, but recently we've been receiving consistently bad products.Some of them are harder, almost greenish in color and break into small, dangerous shards when chewed. Not sure if this is a problem with the batch, the baking process, the shelf-age, or something else.One such shard lodged itself into my dog's esophagus and became infected, which caused severe swelling. He was in pain and unable to bark or eat solid foods for more than a week. He was sedated, biopsied and given antibiotics, which eventually reduced the swelling, but there is still a visible lump from the damaged tissue. It cost us hundreds of dollars and a lot of agony.To be clear, some of these appear safe--if you've seen good ones and bad ones, you can probably tell the difference. But the bad ones nearly killed my dog, and nothing is worth taking that risk again.Absolutely unforgivable quality assurance on this product, and you should buy them at your own risk.
Style: Flavor Name: Cheese | Size: 3.3 Ounce (Pack of 1)

Author: Aineadele
Title: Dog LOVES it, but a little dryer than past experience. Possible choking hazard.
Body: I have a 15 lb, 11 month old schnauzer puppy-and he's a huge chewer. This dog gets into EVERYTHING. Never had a dog that destroyed so many toys, so quickly. Had to stop buying stuffed toys almost completely, as he tears off pieces of fabric and swallows them-or more recently, sawed off one of his teeth by trying to eat a strand of string he torn out of a toy (I was mortified and threw the toy away. It barely lasted a few minutes before being destroyed.) I now search for toys that offer a challenging chew factor while still giving him the satisfaction of feeling like he destroyed it (he seems to mostly be interested in things he can tear up, and ignores toys like nylabones or other inedible chews).Himalayan chews offer him the joys of both chewing heavily and eating the toy. I love this idea because it actually occupies my dog for extended periods of time, giving me peace of mind to relax, instead of chasing him around the house scolding him for stealing toilet paper rolls and tissue from the trash cans, or clothing from the laundry, and leaving trails of debris everywhere.When I saw this on Amazon, I got so excited, because the price was great. I recently bought a smaller one at the store called YakyChew, which my dog loved and ended up being awesome for him. The chew from the store was about half the size, and cost about the same, so the idea of getting twice as much chew for the same price was nice.However, this larger chew ended up being dryer than the previous store bought one. The dryness enabled my dog to chew a small piece off of the chew, which posed a choking hazard. As my dog loves to swallow pieces of his toys, this was not good. I immediately threw away the small piece, and now he will be supervised more closely while finishing this chew. I liked the smaller one I bought in the store before, due to it being more chewy than this, while still being hard and offering a definite chewing challenge to my dog. My dog was not able to chew off pieces and safely chewed it all the way down to a nub. I would recommend Himalayan style chews in general, but this particular one was too dry. It may have been a dryer batch, or maybe it's the consistency of this variety/brand. Just be careful to watch your dog if you order, especially if they like to swallow pieces of things. I may go back to buying at the store.
Style: Flavor Name: Cheese | Size: 3.3 Ounce (Pack of 1)

Author: Katie
Title: I don't trust it
Body: I purchased the Large Himalayan chew for my 9 month old husky (she has all her adult teeth, and I did properly size by weight). She LOVED the chew. Like seriously obsessed with it. And before I purchased I did a couple hours of research to see if it was safe. After purchasing though, I had a couple concerns:1. She chewed quickly. She's not a super aggressive chewer irnfood obsessed. But she loves cheese (hence, she was ecstatic about the chew). She chewed a full inch off in about 30 minutes before I took it away from her. I guarantee if I left it with her it would've been gone in less than 3 hours.2. The chews are VERY hard. I think too hard. And like I said, my dog has all her adult teeth in. I don't think the dogs saliva breaks down the chew fast enough for it to not be too hard on their teeth. Fortunately it didn't break through to the pulp, but it did cost us a vet visit and a dental work with anesthesia to smooth the tooth over and seal it to prevent any future decay or tartar buildup. ($600)3.  Even when microwaved, the chew was still too HARD. I thought it was super cool that you could microwave the chew and make it into a crunchy treat. But even still the treat was too hard for me to feel safe giving it to my dog. Especially after the chipped tooth incident. I opted to microwave the remaining chew, after it was immediately removed from the microwave, cut it into small chunks while it was still a little warm and pliable, and then soak the chunks in water to soften them up. It still took 3-4 hours to partially soften each piece. I even had one piece I soaked overnight and had to throw a portion of it away because it was still rock solid like a pebble.Overall, my dog loved the product, my vet, wallet, and sanity did not. I do not feel comfortable leaving this chew with my pup, surpervised or not.A broken molar is simply not worth the risk. Especially so young! Proceed with great caution if you consider purchasing these!

Date: Reviewed in the United States on October 16, 2016
Author: Sky
Title: Himalayan dog chews last for hours, don’t smell and don’t involve cattle genitalia
Body: After being admonished by my new dog’s foster mother about the evils of rawhides, I started looking into alternative options.  My internet research suggested: Benebone, Himalayan Dog Chews, Pig Ears, Bully Sticks and Hooves/Horns/Antlers.  I have a 45lb black labrador.1) Benebone – my dog likes her benebone but it only keeps her attention for about 10-30 minutes at a time.2) Himalayan Dog Chews – my dog loves these!  They are expensive, but they don’t have a weird odor.  One large chew lasts for about a week.  She will spend a couple of hours per chewing session (approximately 6-10 hours per chew).  Unfortunately they are about as messy as the pig ears, and she leaves little bits of Yak cheese flakes.  When they get small, I microwave the remaining pieces for 30 to 45 seconds.  They puff up and make a quick crunchy treat (but a huge mess).  I have tried purchasing these from both Amazon and Petsmart.  Amazon is cheaper and the quality seems to be better.  (One of my Petsmart chews broke in half almost immediately after the start of a chew session).  *Update: I have stopped giving these to my dog because they frequently break in to small hard chunks, and I worry about my dog choking.3) Pig Ears – my dog loves these!  Made in the USA (of course)!  They are messy and they smell.4) Bully sticks – male cow penises.  I hear good things about these chews.  However odor is an issue, and they are expensive.  *Update: These are my new favorite dog treat.  They smell like smegma.  However, they are not messy, they keep my dog busy for a few hours and my dog loves them.5) Hooves/Horns/Antlers – I saw several negative reviews from people who had to pay for extensive dental work after giving these to their dogs.  Personally I will need to check with my vet first before considering one of these options.
Style: Flavor Name: Cheese | Size: 3.3 Ounce (Pack of 1)

Author: Mr. & Mrs. Lewis
Title: Almost the perfect dog chew for Frenchies!
Body: My frenchies are voracious chewers, and I can't trust them with anything. They destroy "extra durable" nylabones so quickly and eat the plastic chunks, so those are out. Bully sticks are more healthy, but for these funny shaped dogs they just won't work - they were chocking on the big, stringy pieces they were getting off. We tried deer antlers, and were reasonably happy with them - but as the dogs age, I was worried that they were a bit too hard. A friend of mine posted a photo of his dog with his "himalayan bone" and I was intrigued. He said this lasted his big lab/pit mix forever - which I hoped would translate into my dogs not being able to destroy it the first day.Positives:Natural material - so safe for dogs to eat the pieces they get offOnly can get off small pieces - no worries about choking on bit-off piecesDoesn't smellDogs love themThe last chunk can be microwaved for a quick/safe treat - instead of throwing it awayNegatives:If the dogs were left to their own devices with this treat, they would have it gone in a day. We give it to them for an hour at a time so that they last and so that the dog didn't just get a 1/4 lb chunk of cheeseThey are a little messy - so don't put them on something you can't easily clean. We often have a "dog sheet" we throw down under them when they chew these, and toss it in the wash afterwards. They don't stain, just get slobbery and crumbly.

Title: Great idea, not for extreme chewers
Body: Got this as an experiment for my 68-lb german shepherd/rotty mix.  Also tried the size up from this one (70-lb., x-large).  She is an extremely powerful chewer and will stay focused on a toy for hours on end.  She was gaining weight from all the bones so we switched her to Nylabone which she loves.  The Nylabone for powerful chewers last her about a week and within a day they get really sharp so we were looking for a long-lasting, healthy alternative that was cost-effective.  She had this one and the x-large gone in five minutes--she chewed them like they were biscuits.  It was worth a try, she absolutely loved them both but they could not withstand her jaws.  We also tried a Rocky Mountain Antler and that one is still in play.  It has no odor, doesn't leave a mess, and she seems to really love it.  As for the Himalayan Dog Chew, seems like a great idea, only two or three ingredients, no smell, no mess, but just wasn't strong enough for our pup.

Author: John
Title: Satisfying but Short
Body: My girlfriend and I have two Australian Shepherds, which are notorious for their high energy. For about the past year, we have used nylabones to help them focus some of their energy at times when we are both busy. Now, this product obviously tries to differentiate itself from the rest in a number of ways; and for the most part, it excels in those ways, but it has some drawbacks of its own.I'll hold off on writing out an itemized list of the pros and cons, and just make this short. Basically, this product only satisfied part of what we were looking for. We didn't like that the Nylabone tends to "shred" and cause the dogs to choke on the small bits, and sometimes even cut their gums. These chews definitely did not have this problem. The main downsides are that it's kind of smelly, which I completely expected it to, and that the dogs went through them in a couple of days. Well, really, one dog stole the other's when he'd finished his own, so each chew only lasted about a day. And that's really the other main reason we decided to try this.So overall, I'd have to say that for the price of about $10, and for it to last only a day, I can't see us buying any more of these. For that kind of price point I feel buying a rubber chew toy, or a bag of treats would be a better value.  I could see this being a good purchase for some, though. Perhaps our dogs are too "chewy".
Style: Flavor Name: Cheese | Size: 3.3 Ounce (Pack of 1)

Title: Throwing up pieces 2 days later. Be cautious giving to strong chewers.
Body: I have given a few of these chews to my 45lb boston terrier/shepherd mix. Fast forward two days later to 3am and the poor pup was throwing up those chunks in my bed :( She is also extremely gassy. I'm keeping an eye on her to make sure no pieces end up stuck in her intestines. I may still get these in the future but buy the ones meant for small dogs and just microwave them into the puff chew. I haven't decided, but if your dog is a chewer rather than a licker I'd be leery of giving them this product.

Author: Audra Rabroker
Title: I'm sure this treat is good for many dogs
Body: I'm sure this treat is good for many dogs. However, three days after chewing on this treat, my dog began having diarrhea, vomiting, and refused to eat and drink. I was only allowing my dog to chew on it for an hour a day and under supervision. After examining his vomit, I saw it consisted of only hard popcorn-like chunks. I took it and my pooch to the vet. $350 later, turns out that my dog was unable to digest the chew. He almost ended up with a bowel obstruction. He ended up going home with prescribed food and digestive medications as well as an injection and antibiotics. Needless to say, my dog will never be given this treat again. For those of you wanting to try it out, my suggestion is that you monitor your dog very closely during chewing and to start out slow. This way you can see if your dog is able to digest the product safely.
Style: Flavor Name: Cheese | Size: 3.3 Ounce (Pack of 1)

Author: Gretna Khaleesi
Title: Not worth it
Body: I saw this on SharkTank and thought it would be great for my power chewer.  I have two dogs (one <10 lbs, one is 11 lbs).  I bought the large (for 55-lb dogs).  My chihuahua-beagle mix (the 11 lb dog) managed to eat it in less than 2 days once she realized that it was edible.  The first day she had it she just carried it around like it was a security toy, then the second day she realized it was edible.  By the end of day 3 it was down to the microwavable piece.  When it gets to the end piece, the instructions say to microwave it.  This causes it to stink like no other, and caused my power chewer to second guess it.  I give this three stars instead of two stars, because my other dog who doesn't do bones, rawhides, or other chews, enjoyed the microwaved end piece.  She enjoyed it so much that she actually managed to steal some more from her sister.  Overall, I would not buy this again as it costs the same as a Blue Wilderness Elk (medium) Bone and lasted less than a tenth as long.

Author: K. Webb
Title: DANGEROUS!!
Body: These chews fracture teeth.  They are too hard.  They taste good, so dogs chew them enthusiastically, and thus fracture their upper, rear carnasial teeth, and rear molars.  I brush my dogs' teeth almost daily, so I became aware of this relatively quickly, but most people won't even know the teeth are fractured until possibly years later, and they won't know how it happened.  My terrier has slab fractures of both rear carnasials, and a chunk broken out of one upper molar from just a couple sessions with this bone.  She's only a couple of years old.  I won't buy these again, and I hope others won't either.  They aren't worth the risk.

Author: 🔹 Catrinka 🔹
Title: Not a good choice for aggressive chewers...but a delicious option for those dogs who savor their chews
Body: You would think that between a 110 lb dog and a 16 lb dog, the big guy would be the most destructive chewer, right?  Not so in our household.Our huge German Shepherd loves these Himalayan Chews every bit as much as our little terrier.  But he holds his gently between his front paws and carefully works on it, softening the chew so that he can scrape off bits of it.  Even this way, he can get it down to a nub in 3-4 hours.Our small terrier, on the other hand, isn't allowed to have these anymore.  For starters, this is the only chew or cookie that she's SO crazy about that she'll try to attack her huge brother shepherd (who she normally loves) to try to get one of these away from him.  Not a good plan...he's patient with her but that only goes so far.  As far as chewing it, she's always been a very aggressive chewer and can demolish one of these quickly.  Because of that, I worry about choking on large chunks and no longer allow her to have them.  This means that the big guy can only have his under supervision.  Otherwise, she'll go racing over and attack him, grab it, and race away before he even knows what hit him.  Then we have a very disproportionate dog squabble on our hands.**IMPORTANT NOTE: Never seal up an already-chewed Himalayan Dog Chew in a plastic bag.  It's important that they dry out between chewing sessions so that they don't get bacteria or mold growing on them.  Since I generally give my shepherd a chew for just an hour or so at a time, he doesn't finish it all at once.  I simply put it up somewhere out of his reach so that air can reach it.What I really like about these (besides my shepherd's enthusiasm when he gets one) is that they don't really get stinky like bully sticks and many other long-chew options.  I also like that this is a Fair Trade product. They're produced by a consortium of about 900 farmers in Nepal using their own yaks and cattle.If you're interested in more details, the company's website goes into detail about how they are made.  In a nutshell, the milk is boiled for hours, then hand-cranked in a centrifuge to remove the fat, then coagulated with lime juice and salt.  The solids are then washed free of the lime and salt and squeezed in burlap bags for weeks to remove the moisture.  Finally, they're cut to shape and strung on rope for drying/cooking with sun and smoke.  The end result are rock-hard chews.  One bit of information I found interesting is that the top 10-15% are taken and marketed as dog chews.  The remaining 85-90% are used for local human consumption.  I keep telling my dogs that they've got it better than most people.  Now, if I could only get them to read this as proof.All natural ingredients: yak milk, cow milk, salt, lime juice.  Contains no chemicals or preservatives.
Style: Flavor Name: Cheese | Size: 3.3 Ounce (Pack of 1)

Author: Bocchini2012
Title: Not sure whats up with this product
Body: We have purchased several of these Dog Chews. At first we really were thrilled with these. Our dogs just loved them so much. Also, these last a long time (if you only allow your dog to have access them for limited intervals of time) if you are able to have them all day they will go much faster.It seems not every bone is created equal. The batches all seem different. I have two dogs and there seems to always be one bone that they are very interested in and another that they just won't touch. It isn't that my dogs just want what the other one has because none of them will touch it.It always seem that the one that they are interested in seems to go a lot faster (like it's softer) Maybe it is easier to chew? The one that they didn't want seems to look like it was burnt during the baking process? I don't know. We bought four bones, two of which were highly desired and two that were not. We read that if you soak them in water or broth they will be interested again... this did somewhat work but we had to soak them frequently in order to maintain interest.These chews are pretty pricey, and I want to buy them again I just would like to see more of a consistency in the chews. I think the ones that are burnt are just too hard for my dogs and they hurt them to chew on them (their teeth were bleeding:() So I don't blame them for not being interested. It's too bad because they highly recommended on other sites and I like the benefits that the chew offers to my dogs for their overall health. Maybe in the future this company will offer more consistency in their product and what we received was maybe just a bad batch. As for now I think I will hold off on purchasing again.
Style: Flavor Name: Cheese | Size: 3.3 Ounce (Pack of 1)

Additionally, I stupidly paid fifteen bucks for the same size stick from a specialty dog product company (via catalog) who I won't name here. 8 or 9 bucks through Amazon is obviously a good deal for this treat.
Style: Flavor Name: Cheese | Size: 3.3 Ounce (Pack of 1)

Date: Reviewed in the United States on February 8, 2013
Author: CDRUSNRET
Title: OUR SHIH-POO, DOLLY, ABSOLUTELY LOVES IT.
Body: Our, Shih-Poo, Dolly, is almost two, but she still loves to chew like a puppy.  So it has been a challenge to find something that is not only appealing to her, but is safe for her and good for her at the same time.  I think that we have found it with the Himalayan Dog Chew.  She is excited to get it every time that we get it out for her.  We limit her time with it to about an hour no more than twice a day and only when we are watching her, but so far it is a winner.  We ordered one for our older and much larger black lab - rottweiler mix, Trips, but she didn't want to have anything to do with it.  So, Dolly has a replacement when her first one is gone.  We also ordered one for our son's bulldog-pit bull mix, Rudy, and he loves it.  So two out of three of our dogs give it five stars.
Style: Flavor Name: Cheese | Size: 3.3 Ounce (Pack of 1)

Date: Reviewed in the United States on December 24, 2012
Author: A. Quint
Title: Dog loves it, but not long-lasting
Body: From the description one would expect this would be more along the lines of a bone as far as length of time it would take to wear down.  As other reviewers have noted, however, this wasn't the case.  Unlike some reviewers whose dogs demolished it in an hour, ours (a 40 lb Portuguese Water Dog) did get 4 chewing sessions from it (a total of maybe 2 hours), with the end of each session being of her choosing.  I opted for the large size rather than the medium because it seemed that the medium size was the one where reviewers reported dogs encountering trouble from pieces breaking off.  Small pieces did break off but they were small enough to not cause any problem, and my hunch is that the greater diameter of the large size chew takes care of some of that tendency.  As far as reports of digestive problems from ingesting pieces, our dog encountered none, despite the fact that she has a somewhat sensitive stomach.  One odd thiing that happened was that in handing her the bone after it was half eaten, it dropped on the tile floor and broke completely (and cleanly) in half! As far as buying them again, if the chews were less expensive or lasted longer, I'd probably get them with some regularity. As it is, I think the only time I might buy them would be for our twice yearly cross-country drives,when we could reward  her with it at then end of a long day of being stuck in a car.
Style: Flavor Name: Cheese | Size: 3.3 Ounce (Pack of 1)

Date: Reviewed in the United States on December 18, 2012

Date: Reviewed in the United States on October 13, 2012
Author: J. Russell
Title: 5 out of 6 love them
Body: We have 6 rescue dogs of all shapes and sizes and all but one love the Himalayan Chews.  I imagine even he does eat them but he just doesn't run me over when the box containing them arrives.  I have to always look for deals and bargins because they are a bit costly, but considering how much treats cost, and that I have had to stop giving chicken jerky, well in fact all treats from China that doesn't leave me with a lot of options. Plus it isn't calorie laden and one of our little guys has become pretty chubby since arriving at our house last year. I think the coolest thing though is how you just pop the little pieces that are left behind (little 1/2 inch pieces) in the microwave for 37 seconds and you have yourself a yaky puff.  I just have to save the puffs until I get at least 4 for the little dogs so we don't start anything.  The one downside, aside from the cost, is that they can be noisy when it is lights out. One of our guys decides he wants to go to town on one of the large ones just as we all get tucked in for the night. Then I have to get up and walk around and pick them all up so he can't get to any of them and put them up for the night or I would never get to sleep. Oh, one more con, if you step on them barefoot, ouch. But again, the pros definitely outweigh the cons. My little ones were all getting sick on bully sticks, vomiting, diarrhea, the whole nine yards, but nothing with the Himalayan Chews.
Style: Flavor Name: Cheese | Size: 3.3 Ounce (Pack of 1)

Date: Reviewed in the United States on June 15, 2012
Author: geoffory
Title: Great clean treat
Body: ATTENTION: Don't throw the treat away as others have, read below:I first learned of this treat from a booth at the Portland Pet Expo, and it has turned out to be an excellent, safe chew for our golden retriever puppy. When we first gave it to her, she absolutely loved it and chewed it for 15+ minutes straight, which was quite an attention span for our then 11 week old puppy. The pet expo sold samples at a discount, but said the retail price for this size chew was ~$24, so I was glad to find it on amazon for so much less.The himalayan chew is a combination of cow and goat cheeses, which is smoked for 7 months to produce a very hard chew which softens with puppy slobber. It does not stain, smell, or splinter. The only potential risk is a choking hazard as the chew gets small (what bone doesn't have this risk?). However, we learned a trick at the pet expo that most people here don't know:DON'T throw away the treat. When it gets so small you worry about choking, take it away and let it dry then microwave it for 10-15 seconds. The small chunck will get 3+ times larger, and will be less dense as a result. Now it is safe again to give to your pet as a quick treat. This way there is no waste, and your pet enjoys every last bit of it.EDIT: I have noticed it takes more like a minute in the microwave to fully expand. Your results may vary depending on the microwave power - just keep an eye on it and stop when it is no longer expanding.Now that we have had two himalayan chews around the house for five weeks, our golden isn't quite as crazy about it as when we first got it, but she will still happily chew it over most of her toys and treats, and she hasn't finished either one yet. She still won't chew it for more than 15-20 minutes at a time, so it has time to dry out and harden again between chewing sessions. For larger dogs and more agressive chewers, I would expect that it wouldn't last nearly as long since it will stay softer as they keep chewing for longer times.
Style: Flavor Name: Cheese | Size: 3.3 Ounce (Pack of 1)

Date: Reviewed in the United States on November 21, 2011
Author: Frankie
Title: Great all natural long lasting entertainment!
Body: I am now on my third package of Himilayan dog chews from Amazon.  They are amazing and you can't beat the free shipping from the suppliers on Amazon!  My search for a long lasting chew started when our lab/doberman puppy was only about 3-4 months old.  I had read so many good things about bully sticks so I ordered them and then just about threw up when I smelled them!  I tried to look over it, gave it to our pup (who loved it) but then not only did it smell while he was eating it, but his breath was stinky for a while afterwards!  Plus, I'd say the bully stick didn't seem to last much longer than a regular (non-stinky) rawhide.  Then I ordered the Himilayan dog chew.  He wasn't sure how to approach it since it is literally rock hard.  But, then he started scrapping it with his teeth.  He isn't the type of dog to take big bites so he's never gotten any big hunks off of it.  One chew last weeks since we usually save it for an after dinner snack/entertainment (1-2 hours at a time).  Not only does the Himalyan dog chew last a really long time, it also barely smells at all unless you hold it to your nose!  And, at that, it's just a smoked gouda type smell so it's not repulsive like a bully stick.  Plus, it seems to keep our pups breath smelling much better than if he doesn't have it!  We had actually taken a Himalayan dog chew with us on a road trip to my parents house and their dog (9 year old lab mix) actually snuck into our bag and stole the cheese!  This is actually a very surprising thing because their dog has NEVER been a chewer.  If given something hard, she actually just hides it and never eats it.  So, to see her take the cheese and bite small pieces off, I knew she must have loved it!  On our next visit I made sure to have an extra piece of cheese just for her.  Needless to say, I cannot recommend trying this out enough!  If it ends up your dog didn't like it, you just tried one more item in an attempt to make them happy.  If they love it though, you will have found a great investment in your dogs health and happiness!  Our pup LOVES his cheese!
Style: Flavor Name: Cheese | Size: 3.3 Ounce (Pack of 1)
